    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-08-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-08-20T13:00:00-05:00" n="541"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d541">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.516/223: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CWS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-08-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >August 20, 1932—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 3:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>178. Referring to paragraph No. 3, Department’s telegram No. 62, August 12, 5
                    p.m., I received today the following reply from the Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of your letter of August
                                1st<note n="49" xml:id="d541fn49">Not printed.</note> referring to
                            the bank deposits of American citizens made in foreign currency in banks
                            in Chile.</p>
                        <p>I do not believe it possible at this time to anticipate anything with
                            respect to the application in all its aspects of law No. 5107, but I can
                            assure Your Excellency that in case any deposit of an American citizen
                            in foreign currency should be expropriated in whole or in part under any
                            law or regulation, the corresponding effective and adequate compensation
                            will be made in accordance with the guarantees which the political
                            constitution and the laws grant to the inhabitants of the Republic.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Please advise me whether you consider reply satisfactory. The reply uses the
                    phrase “adequate and effective compensation” which I used in my letter of June
                    9th to the Minister for Foreign Affairs. If you desire I can reply to the
                    Minister’s letter and reiterate our interpretation of “effective compensation”
                    but under the circumstances this would seem to be unnecessary.</p>
                <p>In accordance with the Department’s telegram No. 62, August 12, 5 p.m., I
                    prepared a memorandum of my various conversations with <persName
                        corresp="#p_DCG1">Dávila</persName> and the Minister for Foreign Affairs.
                    Last Wednesday I discussed the memorandum with <persName corresp="#p_DCG1"
                        >Dávila</persName> and with the Minister for Foreign Affairs and with
                    certain minor changes they accepted it and it now <pb facs="0585" n="481"
                        xml:id="pg_481"/> has been filed in the Foreign Office. It summarized the
                    several conversations already reported and I therefore will not telegraph it
                    unless you so instruct. A copy of it was transmitted in the air mail which left
                    here Thursday.</p>
                <p>Political situation continues obscure. In the pouch which left here Thursday I
                    transmitted a despatch reviewing the situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
